            ContentJson = """{"passingScore":80,"questionsPerQuiz":8,"shuffleOptions":true,"showExplanationsAfterSubmit":true,"questions":[{"id":"sc1","text":"What is a work center in the Scheduling module?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"A customer location where finished goods are delivered"},{"id":"b","text":"A physical or logical production resource (machine or workstation) where operations are performed and capacity is consumed","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"A storage bin in the warehouse"},{"id":"d","text":"A named group of employees on the same shift"}],"explanation":"A work center is a production resource — a CNC machine, an assembly station, an inspection bench. Scheduling revolves around work centers because they are where capacity is consumed. Each has a code, name, daily capacity hours, efficiency %, and machine count."},{"id":"sc2","text":"A machine operator wants to know what to run next on a specific machine. Which tab should they use?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Schedule"},{"id":"b","text":"Dispatch — select the work center, click Load, and read the priority-ordered queue","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Run History"},{"id":"d","text":"Shifts"}],"explanation":"The Dispatch tab is the floor-operator view. Pick a work center, click Load, and you get a ranked queue of operations in execution order — sequence, scheduled start, setup/run hours, priority, and due date."},{"id":"sc3","text":"What does the Efficiency % field on a work center represent?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The percentage of jobs completed on time"},{"id":"b","text":"A realism factor on capacity — 100% means the center hits its rated capacity, lower values account for downtime, rework, and changeovers","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The markup percentage applied to labor cost"},{"id":"d","text":"The percentage of the work center that is currently scheduled"}],"explanation":"Efficiency % is a realism factor applied to capacity. At 100% the center is assumed to hit its rated daily capacity; setting it to, say, 85% tells the scheduler to expect downtime, rework, and changeovers, so it plans less aggressively."},{"id":"sc4","text":"You click Run Scheduler on the Schedule tab. How does the forward pass place operations?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"It starts from each job's due date and works backward"},{"id":"b","text":"It starts from today and places work as early as capacity allows (capacity-driven)","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"It places all operations at the same start time"},{"id":"d","text":"It only schedules operations that are already locked"}],"explanation":"Run Scheduler runs a forward pass: it starts from today and places work as early as capacity allows — capacity-driven. There is no direction chooser on the screen; the button always runs forward. Backward is a recorded run direction (shown in the Run History Direction column) but is not selectable from this screen today."},{"id":"sc5","text":"An operation is already set up on a machine and must not be moved by the scheduler. What do you do?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Delete the operation and re-add it after scheduling"},{"id":"b","text":"On the Schedule tab, click the lock icon on that operation's row to lock it","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Mark the work center inactive"},{"id":"d","text":"Set the operation's status to Cancelled"}],"explanation":"Click the lock icon on the operation's row in the Schedule tab. A locked operation is fixed — the scheduler plans everything else around it and never re-times it. Click the icon again to unlock."},{"id":"sc6","text":"What determines a shift's Net Hours?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Number of machines multiplied by daily capacity"},{"id":"b","text":"End time minus start time minus break minutes","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The efficiency percent of the assigned work center"},{"id":"d","text":"The total scheduled hours across all operations"}],"explanation":"Net Hours is the productive time in a shift: end time − start time − break minutes. Shifts are global (shared across all work centers), and their net hours feed the capacity available for scheduling."},{"id":"sc7","text":"Where can you see how many operations a scheduler run placed and how many conflicts it detected?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The Dispatch tab"},{"id":"b","text":"The Run History tab — each run records its date, direction, status, operations scheduled, and conflicts detected","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The Work Centers tab"},{"id":"d","text":"The KPI chips at the top of the page"}],"explanation":"The Run History tab is the audit log of every scheduler execution. Each row shows the run date, direction (Forward/Backward), status (Completed/Running/Failed), the number of operations scheduled, and the number of conflicts detected."},{"id":"sc8","text":"Which fields are required when creating a work center?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Only Code and Name"},{"id":"b","text":"Code, Name, Daily Capacity (Hours), Efficiency %, and Number of Machines","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Code, Name, Labor Cost / Hour, and Burden Rate / Hour"},{"id":"d","text":"Every field on the dialog is required"}],"explanation":"The required fields are Code, Name, Daily Capacity (Hours), Efficiency %, and Number of Machines — these are exactly what the scheduler needs to compute capacity. Description, Sort Order, Labor Cost / Hour, Burden Rate / Hour, and the Active toggle are optional."},{"id":"sc9","text":"What is a 'conflict' in the context of a scheduler run?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Two users editing the same work center at once"},{"id":"b","text":"A scheduling problem the run detects, most commonly a work center scheduled beyond its capacity","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"A duplicate job number"},{"id":"d","text":"A shift whose end time is before its start time"}],"explanation":"A conflict is a scheduling problem surfaced by the run — typically a work center loaded beyond its available capacity. The run reports the conflict count so you can react (add capacity, move work, or adjust due dates) rather than silently slipping a due date."},{"id":"sc10","text":"On the Dispatch tab, the Load button is disabled. Why?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The scheduler has never been run"},{"id":"b","text":"No work center has been selected yet — choose one from the selector to enable Load","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"All operations are locked"},{"id":"d","text":"The current user lacks scheduling permission"}],"explanation":"The Load button on the Dispatch tab is disabled until you pick a work center from the selector. The dispatch list is work-center-specific, so the system needs to know which center's queue to load before it can populate the table."},{"id":"sc11","text":"Where do the operations that appear on the schedule come from?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"They are created manually on the Schedule tab"},{"id":"b","text":"They come from the operations defined on your jobs — scheduling sequences the work the jobs already describe","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"They are generated from purchase orders"},{"id":"d","text":"They are imported from the accounting system"}],"explanation":"Scheduling doesn't invent work. Each scheduled row references a job number and an operation title — the operations come from the jobs themselves. The scheduler's job is to sequence and time that existing work against work-center capacity."},{"id":"sc12","text":"You change a work center's daily capacity and efficiency. What is the effect?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Nothing changes until the next billing cycle"},{"id":"b","text":"The values feed the scheduler's capacity math, so future runs plan against the updated capacity","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"All existing scheduled operations are immediately deleted"},{"id":"d","text":"The work center is automatically set to inactive"}],"explanation":"Daily Capacity (Hours) and Efficiency % are primary inputs to how the scheduler computes available capacity. Keeping them accurate is what makes the schedule reflect your shop's real throughput; updated values are used by subsequent scheduler runs."}]}"""
